@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Program History"
1.  Introduction


Whilst beta-testing @{"Mathscript 3.0" link "Mathscript" 0}, I found myself wishing there was a function
to remove brackets that I'd placed incorrectly.  MS3.0 users will know that
the only way to do this is to drag-select and cut the formula within the
brackets, delete the brackets and then paste the snipped section back into
the main formula.  Yaaaaaaawn.  Not only is it tedious, it's all too easy to
make a slip and end up deleting the wrong bit of the formula, or not cutting
all the pieces that you want to keep.  There had to be a better way.......

So, armed only with a copy of the Commodore ARexx manual, an early beta version
of Mathscript and a spare hour or two, I set to work.  The ARexx script you
now have is the first beta version to be released into the outside world,
and the first to do everything I wanted it to do when I started writing it.

A quick example...

Say you've entered the formula:

   x = a + (b + c)
   
but you really wanted:

   x = a + b + c
   

In the pre-StripCode days you'd have to select the b + c part, copy it into
the clipboard, select the (), delete them, then paste the b + c back.

Now with StripCode, all you have to do is position the cursor somewhere within
the () and run the script.  The brackets will automatically be removed,
leaving you with the required formula, without any trouble.


But why stop there!!!  StripCode can also return super and subscript sections
to normal, remove root symbols and under/overlines.  And the next version will
also make the coffee :-)  See @{"Usage" link "Usage" 0} for full instructions.


@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Introduction"
2.  Installation


Copy StripCode.ms wherever you like, though Mathscript:Rexx/ might be a
good place to start...

If you intend using the script a lot, consider linking it to a Function key
in the Mathscript ARexx menu, for single key operation.

Quite easy really, which is just as well since I don't feel like writing
an Installer script :-)


NOTE:  StripCode 1.1 is designed for use with MathScript 3.1.  It will
definitely work in parts with MathScript 3.0, but has not been fully tested
to ensure 100% backwards compatability.  If you haven't yet upgraded to
MathScript 3.1, do so!!!


@{"Return to Contents" link "Main" 0}
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "Author Info"
@prev "Installation"
3.  Usage


To strip the formula code from a section of formula, place the cursor within
the section to be stripped and run the script.

If we use | to represent to cursor, then:

x = a + (b +|c ) becomes x = a + b + c


StripCode can remove the following:

All left, right and paired brackets.
Square Root
Underbar and Overbar
Single and Double Dot
Not, Acute, Greve, Hat, Check, Breve and Tilde
Vector Left, Right and Both
Subscript and Superscript (but not Sub+Superscript) 
nth Root



The actual formula codes checked for are:

^<obj>
_<obj>
\\ul<obj>
\\ol<obj>
\\l<b><obj>
<obj>\\r<b>
\\sqrt<obj>
\\dt<n><obj>
\\not<obj>
\\atilde<obj>
\\aacute<obj>
\\agrave<obj>
\\ahat<obj>
\\abreve<obj>
\\acheck<obj>
\\lvec<obj>
\\rvec<obj>
\\bvec<obj>

Special Cases...

\\rt<obj1><obj2>     Will only remove the <obj1> part, and only if
                    the cursor is within the <obj1> part.  The code
                    will then be changed to <obj1>\\sqrt<obj2>.
                        
<obj>\\up\\sy<x>      Will only work correctly if x is a single character.
                    For codes inserted via the GUI, this will always
                    be true (single dot, double dot etc.)
         
         
If you have nested codes, each run of StripCode will strip the innermost
codes, until no codes remain around the section marked.

e.g:

  x = a + (b + (c +|d)) becomes   x = a + (b + c + d)
  
whereas

  x = a + (b +|(c + d)) becomes   x = a + b + (c + d)
  
  
Notice the difference.  In the first example, the inner brackets are removed,
as they are the nearest codes surrounding the cursor position.  In the second
example, the outer brackets are removed because now the cursor is not within
the section surrounded by the inner brackets.
Remember, the cursor must be INSIDE the section affected by the code you want
to remove.  This is especially important for the codes that add marks above the
formula section, such as the vector codes.  Here you must ensure the cursor is
within the part of the formula below the mark, and not alongside it.  If there
is just a single character below the mark, it is very easy to get the cursor
in the wrong place.  To avoid this, try drag-selecting the section, but make
sure the mark is not included in the highlighted section.
Trust me, it does work!



Note on nth Root:

This is stripped in two steps.  First you must strip the root index, leaving
just a plain square root.  Then you can strip the square root as normal.

e.g:
            ___                  ___
         x /                    /
         \\/  y    becomes    x\\/  y  , and then simply xy
         

