@node "Amiga" "Chris's Amiga :-)"
@next "PC"
@prev "PC"
My Amiga is currently configured as follows:


A4000 desktop
CyberStorm060/50 Mk.1, CyberSCSI Mk.1
CyberVision64 2MB
2MB Chip RAM
40MB 70ns CyberStorm Fast RAM
8MB 70ns Motherboard Fast RAM
  
420MB Samsung IDE Drive, 850MB Maxtor IDE Drive
Apple Internal SCSI 4X CD-ROM
Iomega External SCSI Zip Drive
 
VLab Y/C Internal frame grabber
MasterSound mono 8bit sampler
Microvitec 1438 Monitor
Workbench 3.0 (39.29), Kickstart 3.0 (39.106)


Surprisingly enough, it still manages to remain reasonably cool, even with all
that hardware crammed into the rather small case.  But if I ever meet the
"genius" who designed the A4000 casing, I'll probably end up smacking him across
the head with a large wet haddock.  5.25" drive bays only just long enough to
hold the shortest CDROMs, drive bays that have discrete screw holes rather than
slots, a front panel that takes at least five pairs of hands to remove and 
absolutely no space left over for your fingers to grab hold of stuff when you
want to put something in/take something out.  Gaaaah, I see why replacement
cases are such a good idea...

...so if any of the Eagle guys are reading this, any 4000TE cases (or even
entire systems) needing a good home?  I'm sure I could provide the level of
care that it would require.
@endnode

